{"author":{"id":"138b13306404778af60b1d60d606624fec41556ddac480b2d5f762806ce84fed"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1782958607,"nonce":"Y2wEyyUGPGqYkESCqhl7nI2fiQ4=","kind":"plans","title":"Apply golang-* Skills to kb — Implementation Plan","content_type":"text/markdown"},{"type":3,"timestamp":1782958607,"nonce":"XzkJvJrYL8UTPNlAIjv6xcXDkHo=","body":"# Apply golang-* Skills to kb — Implementation Plan\n\n\u003e **For agentic workers:** REQUIRED SUB-SKILL: Use superpowers:subagent-driven-development to implement this plan task-by-task. Steps use checkbox (`- [ ]`) syntax for tracking.\n\n**Goal:** Apply the findings of an 11-skill golang-* audit to the `kb` codebase — fixing genuine correctness, safety, concurrency, documentation, test-coverage, and tooling gaps while respecting the team's minimal-diff / no-over-engineering stance.\n\n**Architecture:** The codebase is already in strong shape; this is a targeted remediation, not a rewrite. Work proceeds in dependency order: unblock CI first (`go mod tidy`), then apply small correctness/safety fixes (TDD where behavior changes), add docs and tests, then introduce `golangci-lint` as the keystone that enforces the style/modernize/errcheck findings going forward, and finish with CI hardening that needs no external secrets.\n\n**Tech Stack:** Go 1.26.4 (always `GOTOOLCHAIN=auto`), spf13/cobra, modelcontextprotocol/go-sdk, go-git, git-bug, Ginkgo v2 + Gomega, yaml.v3. Build/test via `task`.\n\n**Verification baseline (before any change):** `GOTOOLCHAIN=auto go build ./...` ✅, `go vet ./...` ✅, `gofmt -l .` clean ✅. Full tests require `task test` (provisions pinned gitleaks into ./bin and sets `KB_GITLEAKS`) — a bare `go test ./...` shows false failures because the suite shells out to gitleaks. **Always verify with `task test` / `task test:e2e`, never bare `go test`.** Note: `./bin/kb` may hit SELinux \"Permission denied\"; do not execute the hand-built binary — rely on `task test`.\n\n**Out of scope / deliberately NOT done (with rationale):**\n- Prometheus/OTEL/Grafana/Pyroscope/RUM, `slog` migration for the CLI, `sync.Pool`/GC tuning, speculative benchmarks — inappropriate for a short-lived local CLI + stdio MCP server (OBS-1, BENCH-1, PERF-1/2). The CLI's stderr+exit-code contract is correct.\n- Codecov upload (CI-2) and GoReleaser SBOM/cosign signing (CI-5) — require external accounts/tokens/signing keys and touch release infra; flagged for the maintainer to opt into, not applied autonomously.\n- `llms.txt` (DOC-4) and Example tests (DOC-5) — optional, low priority for an app with only internal packages.\n- Extracting the 7 near-identical tier-search loops (D5) and `spaces`→`strings.Repeat` (D4) — premature abstraction / cosmetic; the team's stance rejects this.\n\n---\n\n## Task 1: Unblock CI — tidy go.sum (DEP-1, HIGH)\n\n**Why first:** `.github/workflows/test.yml` runs `go mod tidy \u0026\u0026 git diff --exit-code`. `go mod tidy -diff` is currently non-empty (missing `golang-jwt/jwt/v5` checksum + ~100 stale `/go.mod` lines), so CI fails on this branch regardless of any other change.\n\n**Files:** Modify `go.sum`.\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Confirm the drift**\n\nRun: `cd /workspace \u0026\u0026 GOTOOLCHAIN=auto go mod tidy -diff`\nExpected: non-empty diff, exit 1.\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Apply tidy**\n\nRun: `GOTOOLCHAIN=auto go mod tidy`\n\n- [ ] **Step 3: Verify clean + still builds**\n\nRun: `GOTOOLCHAIN=auto go mod tidy -diff \u0026\u0026 echo CLEAN \u0026\u0026 GOTOOLCHAIN=auto go build ./...`\nExpected: `CLEAN`, build succeeds.\n\n- [ ] **Step 4: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add go.sum\ngit commit -m \"build: tidy go.sum to satisfy CI tidy gate\"\n```\n\n---\n\n## Task 2: Fix nil-author dereference (E1, MEDIUM, safety)\n\n**Why:** `op.Author().Name()` is called unguarded in `internal/entry/history.go` at lines 23 (`Log`) and 68 (`BodyVersions`). `dag.OpBase.Author()` can return nil — the codebase itself guards this in `operations.go` `Create.Apply` (`if a := op.Author(); a != nil`). A synced entry whose author identity didn't resolve would panic `kb log` / `kb diff`.\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `internal/entry/history.go:23`, `internal/entry/history.go:68`\n- Test: `internal/entry/history_test.go` (or the existing history spec file — locate with `grep -rl \"BodyVersions\\|func.*Log\" internal/entry/*_test.go`)\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Write a failing test** — construct an entry/operation whose `Author()` is nil and assert `Log()` / `BodyVersions()` return an empty author string rather than panicking. (Inspect how existing history specs build entries; reuse that harness. If a nil-author op cannot be constructed through the public API, this finding is theoretical — in that case downgrade to a defensive guard with a comment and skip the test, noting why.)\n\nRun the test: `GOTOOLCHAIN=auto go test ./internal/entry/ -run \u003cSpecName\u003e` — expect FAIL/panic.\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Implement the guard** in both call sites, mirroring `Create.Apply`:\n\n```go\nname := \"\"\nif a := op.Author(); a != nil {\n    name = a.Name()\n}\n// use `name` for LogEntry.Author / BodyVersion.Author\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 3: Verify** — `task test` (entry suite green).\n\n- [ ] **Step 4: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add internal/entry/history.go internal/entry/\u003chistory_test\u003e.go\ngit commit -m \"fix(entry): guard nil author in Log and BodyVersions\"\n```\n\n---\n\n## Task 3: Surface swallowed errors (E2 + E3, LOW, error-handling)\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `internal/bridge/bridge.go:229` (`EnsureGitignore`) and `cmd/kb/commands.go:314` (`show`).\n\n- [ ] **Step 1 (E2):** In `EnsureGitignore`, replace `existing, _ := os.ReadFile(path)` so only not-exist is ignored, any other error is returned — matching the pattern at `commands.go:602-605`:\n\n```go\nexisting, err := os.ReadFile(path)\nif err != nil \u0026\u0026 !os.IsNotExist(err) {\n    return fmt.Errorf(\"read .gitignore: %w\", err)\n}\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 2 (E3):** In `show` (`commands.go:314`), the `Merged` error is currently dropped. Since `id` is already resolved, a non-nil error is always a real git read failure (never not-found). Either surface it or document the swallow. **Decision: surface it** (single-id command, error is meaningful):\n\n```go\nm, mErr := s.Merged(id)\nif mErr != nil {\n    return fmt.Errorf(\"check merged status: %w\", mErr)\n}\nsnap.Merged = m\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 3: Verify** — `task test` green (these paths are covered by show/bridge specs).\n\n- [ ] **Step 4: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add internal/bridge/bridge.go cmd/kb/commands.go\ngit commit -m \"fix: stop swallowing read errors in EnsureGitignore and show\"\n```\n\n---\n\n## Task 4: Drain git-bug channels on early return (C1, MEDIUM, concurrency)\n\n**Why:** `dag.ReadAll` (store.go:150-153 in `List`) and `dag.MergeAll` (sync.go:127-137 in `Pull`) are library producers writing to an **unbuffered** channel with `defer close(out)`; they emit errors mid-stream and keep iterating. The consumers `return` on the first error, so the producer blocks forever on its next send → one leaked goroutine. Benign in the one-shot CLI (process exits), but the **long-lived MCP server** runs `List` on every `recall`, leaking permanently.\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `internal/store/store.go:150-153`, `internal/store/sync.go:127-137`\n- Test: hard to trigger deterministically without a malformed entry; rely on code review + existing list/pull specs staying green. (Do NOT add a flaky goroutine-count test.)\n\n- [ ] **Step 1:** Change both consumers to record the first error, then **continue draining** the channel to completion before returning, e.g.:\n\n```go\nvar ferr error\nfor streamed := range readAllCh {\n    if streamed.Err != nil {\n        if ferr == nil {\n            ferr = streamed.Err\n        }\n        continue // keep draining so the producer goroutine can exit\n    }\n    // ... existing happy-path processing, guarded by `if ferr == nil`\n}\nif ferr != nil {\n    return nil, fmt.Errorf(\"...: %w\", ferr)\n}\n```\n\nApply the analogous shape to `sync.go` `MergeAll` consumer. Preserve existing error-wrapping messages.\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Verify** — `task test` and `task test:e2e` green (list/sync/recall paths unchanged on happy path).\n\n- [ ] **Step 3: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add internal/store/store.go internal/store/sync.go\ngit commit -m \"fix(store): drain dag channels on error to avoid goroutine leak\"\n```\n\n---\n\n## Task 5: Signal-bound root context (C1-cli + C2-concurrency, MEDIUM)\n\n**Why:** `main()` calls `root.Execute()`, giving every command `context.Background()`. The `mcp` subcommand passes `cmd.Context()` into `mcpserver.Serve` as the server lifetime context, but it is never cancellable, so SIGINT/SIGTERM cannot drive graceful shutdown. Standard cobra+signal fix, scoped to `main`.\n\n**Files:** Modify `cmd/kb/main.go` (around the `Execute()` call, ~line 107-112).\n\n- [ ] **Step 1:** Replace `root.Execute()` with a signal-bound context:\n\n```go\nctx, stop := signal.NotifyContext(context.Background(), os.Interrupt, syscall.SIGTERM)\ndefer stop()\nif err := root.ExecuteContext(ctx); err != nil {\n    fmt.Fprintln(os.Stderr, \"error:\", err)\n    os.Exit(1)\n}\n```\n\nAdd imports: `context`, `os/signal`, `syscall`. Keep ctx scoped to `main`; do not store it anywhere.\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Verify** — `GOTOOLCHAIN=auto go build ./...`, `task test`. Confirm `cmd.Context()` is now the cancellable ctx (no behavior change for one-shot commands).\n\n- [ ] **Step 3: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add cmd/kb/main.go\ngit commit -m \"feat(cli): bind root context to SIGINT/SIGTERM for clean MCP shutdown\"\n```\n\n---\n\n## Task 6: Modernize + compile-time interface checks (M1, L1, L2, L3, D1, LOW)\n\n**Why:** These are the items `golangci-lint`'s `modernize` linter (Task 11) will flag; fixing them now keeps that gate green. D1 converts a latent runtime panic into a compile error at near-zero cost.\n\n**Files:** `internal/entry/operations.go`, `internal/store/hygiene.go`, `internal/store/sync.go`.\n\n- [ ] **Step 1 (M1):** `operations.go:226-231` `AddLabel.Apply` — replace the membership loop with `if slices.Contains(s.Labels, op.Label) { return }`. Add `\"slices\"` import.\n\n- [ ] **Step 2 (L1):** Replace `sort.Strings(...)` with `slices.Sort(...)` at `operations.go:233` and `hygiene.go:177`; drop the now-unused `\"sort\"` import in each (swap for `\"slices\"`). **Leave `render.go:122` `sort.SliceStable` as-is** (no `slices` equivalent).\n\n- [ ] **Step 3 (L2/L3):** `operations.go:298,313` `strings.Split(body,\"\\n\")` → `strings.SplitSeq`; `sync.go:164` `strings.Fields(raw)` → `strings.FieldsSeq`. Convert the `for _, x := range` to `for x := range`.\n\n- [ ] **Step 4 (D1):** Add compile-time assertions for all 11 `Operation` implementers in `operations.go`, grouped near the type defs or the interface:\n\n```go\nvar (\n    _ Operation = (*Create)(nil)\n    _ Operation = (*SetStatus)(nil)\n    // ... one per op type: SetBody, SetTitle, AddLink, RemoveLink,\n    // Tombstone, Restore, AddLabel, RemoveLabel, RecordOrigin\n)\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 5: Verify** — `GOTOOLCHAIN=auto go build ./... \u0026\u0026 go vet ./... \u0026\u0026 task test` green.\n\n- [ ] **Step 6: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add internal/entry/operations.go internal/store/hygiene.go internal/store/sync.go\ngit commit -m \"refactor: modernize slices/strings usage and add Operation interface guards\"\n```\n\n---\n\n## Task 7: Package + constructor doc comments (DOC-1, DOC-2, DOC-3, LOW/MEDIUM)\n\n**Why:** 6 of 8 packages lack the package doc comment the documentation skill requires; the 11 exported `New*` operation constructors lack doc comments (revive `exported` will flag these in Task 11). `render` and `mcpserver` already have exemplary package comments — use them as the model.\n\n**Files:** one file per package + `internal/entry/operations.go`.\n\n- [ ] **Step 1 (DOC-1):** Add `// Package main implements the kb command-line interface.` (expand to 1-2 lines on what kb is) above `package main` in `cmd/kb/main.go`.\n\n- [ ] **Step 2 (DOC-2):** Add a `// Package \u003cname\u003e ...` comment to one file in each of: `internal/store/store.go`, `internal/entry/entry.go`, `internal/bridge/bridge.go`, `internal/hooks/hooks.go`, `internal/scan/scan.go`. Each states the package's single responsibility (mirror render/mcpserver style).\n\n- [ ] **Step 3 (DOC-3):** Add a one-line doc comment beginning with the identifier to each exported constructor in `operations.go` (`NewCreate`, `NewSetStatus`, `NewSetBody`, `NewSetTitle`, `NewAddLink`, `NewRemoveLink`, `NewTombstone`, `NewRestore`, `NewAddLabel`, `NewRemoveLabel`, `NewRecordOrigin`). Leave mechanical interface methods (`Id`/`Validate`/`Apply`) as-is per existing convention.\n\n- [ ] **Step 4: Verify** — `GOTOOLCHAIN=auto go build ./... \u0026\u0026 go vet ./...`; spot-check `GOTOOLCHAIN=auto go doc ./internal/store` shows the package comment.\n\n- [ ] **Step 5: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add cmd/kb/main.go internal/store/store.go internal/entry/entry.go internal/entry/operations.go internal/bridge/bridge.go internal/hooks/hooks.go internal/scan/scan.go\ngit commit -m \"docs: add package and operation-constructor doc comments\"\n```\n\n---\n\n## Task 8: Scanner test seam + secret-path tests (TEST-01, MEDIUM)\n\n**Why:** `scan.Scan` is a hard package-level function that forks the real `gitleaks` binary, so every store/bridge test transitively needs the binary and the security-critical \"secret found / clean / scanner errored\" branches in `bridge.Ingest`, `store.Push`, `store.Retier` can't be unit-tested in isolation. Introduce a minimal, idiomatic seam (overridable package var) — not a new abstraction layer.\n\n**Files:** `internal/scan/scan.go` (or the consuming packages), plus new test cases.\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Decide the seam location.** Prefer the smallest change: in `internal/scan`, expose the exec'd implementation behind a package var, e.g. `var scanFn = scanWithGitleaks` and have `Scan` call `scanFn`; tests in-package override `scanFn`. If consumers (bridge/store) need to inject, add a narrow function-typed field/param at their boundary instead. Choose whichever yields the smaller diff after reading the call sites. Keep ONE integration test that still exercises real gitleaks under `task test`.\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Write failing tests** for the previously-untestable branches using the fake: secret-found → quarantine/PushBlocked, clean → proceeds, scanner-errored → error propagates. Place them in the relevant `_test.go` (bridge/store/scan).\n\n- [ ] **Step 3: Implement the seam**, run the new tests green via `task test`.\n\n- [ ] **Step 4: Verify** the real-gitleaks integration test still passes (`task test`), and `task test:e2e` green.\n\n- [ ] **Step 5: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add internal/scan/ internal/bridge/ internal/store/ \u003cnew test files\u003e\ngit commit -m \"test(scan): add injectable scanner seam and cover secret-detection branches\"\n```\n\n---\n\n## Task 9: Fill remaining test gaps (TEST-02, TEST-03, TEST-04, TEST-05, LOW)\n\n**Files:** existing `_test.go` suites.\n\n- [ ] **Step 1 (TEST-02):** Add a cli spec for `promote`/retier WITHOUT `--yes`: feed `\"no\\n\"` via the existing `runIn` helper, assert the entry stays in its original tier (decline path of `confirmRetier`, `commands.go:936`). Optional `\"yes\\n\"` variant.\n- [ ] **Step 2 (TEST-03):** Add a store spec for `Store.Restore` (`store.go:257`): tombstone an entry, `Restore`, assert live again; plus a negative case asserting `Restore` of an unknown id errors.\n- [ ] **Step 3 (TEST-04):** In the existing retier \"blocks promotion\" spec, additionally assert `rb.Error()` (`retier.go:120`) contains the offender id/title and the remediation guidance (\"Rotate the secret\", \"kb purge\") — without asserting the secret value appears.\n- [ ] **Step 4 (TEST-05):** Add `hooks.Merge` negative specs: malformed YAML input and a non-mapping (sequence/scalar) root, asserting the respective wrapped errors.\n- [ ] **Step 5: Verify** — `task test` green; confirm coverage rose on the targeted packages via `task test` output.\n- [ ] **Step 6: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add \u003ctouched _test.go files\u003e\ngit commit -m \"test: cover retier decline, Store.Restore, RetierBlockedError, hooks.Merge errors\"\n```\n\n---\n\n## Task 10: Security hardening (SEC-02, SEC-04, SEC-03, LOW)\n\n**Files:** `internal/store/sync.go` (SetRemote), `internal/scan/scan.go`, `cmd/kb/commands.go`.\n\n- [ ] **Step 1 (SEC-02):** In `SetRemote` (`sync.go:27`), validate the remote name against `^[A-Za-z0-9][A-Za-z0-9._-]*$` and reject dash-leading/option-shaped names, so `git push \u003cremote\u003e --delete \u003cref\u003e` (store.go:333) can never be tricked into argument injection. Add a test for the rejection.\n- [ ] **Step 2 (SEC-04):** In `gitleaksBin()` (`scan.go:25-30`), when `KB_GITLEAKS` is unset, resolve via `exec.LookPath(\"gitleaks\")` and fail closed (clear error) if not found, rather than relying on bare `\"gitleaks\"`. Add/adjust a test.\n- [ ] **Step 3 (SEC-03):** In the `--force` hooks merge read (`commands.go:602`), bound the `lefthook.yml` input size (reject files over a sane cap, e.g. 1 MB) before `yaml.Unmarshal` to prevent a local alias-bomb DoS. Add a test for the over-size rejection.\n- [ ] **Step 4: Verify** — `task test` green.\n- [ ] **Step 5: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add internal/store/sync.go internal/scan/scan.go cmd/kb/commands.go \u003ctests\u003e\ngit commit -m \"fix(security): validate remote name, resolve gitleaks via LookPath, bound lefthook input\"\n```\n\n---\n\n## Task 11: Introduce golangci-lint (LINT-1, LINT-2, CI-1, HIGH) — keystone\n\n**Why:** The single biggest tooling gap — `task lint` is only `go vet` + `gofmt`. golangci-lint enforces errcheck/staticcheck/gosec/errorlint/modernize/revive going forward. Sequenced after manual fixes so the first-run backlog is small.\n\n**Files:** new `.golangci.yml`, modify `Taskfile.yml`, `.github/workflows/lint.yml`.\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: VERIFY the tool + schema.** Do NOT trust a remembered config format. Determine the golangci-lint version to pin (check latest stable release), install it pinned, and confirm the config schema with `golangci-lint config verify`. The audit drafted a **v2-schema** starter (`version: \"2\"`, `linters.enable`, `linters.exclusions`, `linters.settings`, separate `formatters`) — validate it against the version you actually pin.\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Add `.golangci.yml`** using the pragmatic linter set from the Lint/CI audit (errcheck, staticcheck, govet, unused, errorlint, nilerr, forcetypeassert, durationcheck, gosec, bidichk, asciicheck, gocritic, revive, misspell, dupword, predeclared, errname, whitespace, unconvert, ineffassign, usestdlibvars, modernize, intrange, thelper, usetesting, nolintlint; gofmt+goimports as formatters). Drop SQL/HTTP/logging linters (not applicable). Relax errcheck/gosec/funlen/dupl in `_test.go`. Decide G204 handling at the gitleaks exec site: prefer a scoped `//nolint:gosec // pinned repo-controlled binary` over a blanket exclude — verify the exec site first.\n\n- [ ] **Step 3: Pin + wire into Taskfile.** Add golangci-lint to the `tools:` task (pinned version, installed into `./bin`, like gitleaks) and call it from `lint:` alongside/replacing the raw gofmt check.\n\n- [ ] **Step 4: Run it, triage the backlog.** `task lint` (or `./bin/golangci-lint run`). Fix every finding the manual tasks didn't already cover. If the backlog is unexpectedly large, narrow the enabled set or use `issues.new-from-rev` and note what was deferred (no silent suppression — every `//nolint` names a linter + reason).\n\n- [ ] **Step 5: Single-source CI (LINT-2).** Make `.github/workflows/lint.yml` run the SAME entrypoint — preferably `task lint` via `arduino/setup-task` (matching `test.yml`), or `golangci/golangci-lint-action` pinned to the same version. No local/CI drift.\n\n- [ ] **Step 6: Verify** — `task lint` exits 0, `task test` still green, `go build ./...` green.\n\n- [ ] **Step 7: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add .golangci.yml Taskfile.yml .github/workflows/lint.yml \u003cany backlog fixes\u003e\ngit commit -m \"ci: add golangci-lint with pinned version, wire into Taskfile and CI\"\n```\n\n---\n\n## Task 12: CI alignment, no external secrets (CI-1, CI-3, LOW)\n\n**Files:** `Taskfile.yml`, `.github/workflows/security.yml`.\n\n- [ ] **Step 1 (CI-3):** Pin `govulncheck` to a released tag instead of `@latest` in `.github/workflows/security.yml` (reproducible CI). Find the current released version.\n- [ ] **Step 2 (CI-1):** Align `task check` with the CI gate set: ensure it runs `fmt → lint (golangci-lint) → test:e2e` and add a `vuln` task (pinned govulncheck) included in `check`, so \"green locally\" mirrors CI.\n- [ ] **Step 3: Verify** — `task check` runs the full chain and passes (will install pinned govulncheck; allow time).\n- [ ] **Step 4: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add Taskfile.yml .github/workflows/security.yml\ngit commit -m \"ci: pin govulncheck and align 'task check' with CI gates\"\n```\n\n---\n\n## Final verification (before declaring done)\n\n- [ ] `GOTOOLCHAIN=auto go build ./...` — succeeds\n- [ ] `task lint` — exits 0 (golangci-lint clean)\n- [ ] `task test:e2e` — all suites green (unit + e2e)\n- [ ] `GOTOOLCHAIN=auto go mod tidy -diff` — clean\n- [ ] `git log --oneline` — logical, scoped commits; no drive-by changes\n- [ ] Update `CHANGELOG.md` `[Unreleased]` with the user-visible changes (signal handling, security hardening) — internal refactors/tests need no entry.\n- [ ] Re-read this plan's \"Out of scope\" list; surface the deferred items (codecov, SBOM/cosign, llms.txt) to the user as opt-in recommendations.\n\n## Self-review notes\n- Every task maps to a specific audit finding ID. The deferred set is explicitly justified, not dropped silently.\n- No task introduces an abstraction beyond the scanner seam (Task 8), which is the minimum needed to test security-critical branches — justified by the team's own TDD/testing emphasis.\n- Type/name consistency: `scanFn` seam name used consistently in Task 8; `Operation` interface guard names match the 11 op types listed in Task 6."}]}